Managed a team of 60 people to organize a national level technical festival "Renaissance" which is a 3 day long event with seminars, competitions and technical paper presentations.

included.companyName: University of Michigan School of Public Health
included.description: Working across several projects as a UX researcher to conduct user studies, needs assessments brainstorming processes to solve the wicked problems in the public health domain. Having a multidisciplinary background in computer science also allows me to assess the gap between design and its implementation. Conducting feasibility studies of designs and bridging the gap between academics and markets by playing a part in technology transfer.
included.title: UX Researcher, Innovation Studio

included.companyName: University of Michigan - School of Information
included.description: Researched, designed and developed an Amazon Alexa based conversational interface to a cross device virtual lab assistant. Developed context-aware VUIâs to integrate tasks like recording attendance, updating Trello tasks and posting to Slack to reduce time in spent in performing them.
included.title: Interaction Design Research Assistant @ Michigan Information Interaction Lab

included.description: Designed and developed the "19th Century Acts" project which visualizes the extensive work of Ira Aldridge on the world map. Conducted user research to analyze user intentions and developed the website using Django Framework for Python, OpenMaps API for geospatial mapping and custom javascript framework to allow users to explore the database using parameters of time, location, and type of work.
included.title: Data Visualization UX Design & Development @ Stephen S. Clark Library

included.companyName: Innovation Studio @ School of Public Health, University of Michigan
included.description: Conducted research for approaching problems in the public health with a multidisciplinary team to understanding needs in the health domain and translating them into meaningful and facilitating interactions for a variety of stakeholders. My role consisted of conducting user interviews,  contextual inquiry, background research, wireframing, prototyping and usability tests for Traceroot.
included.title: User Experience Design Intern

included.summary: I am a user experience researcher with a multidisciplinary background in Computer Science & Design from the University of Michigan. I like to create intuitive solutions with a user-centered approach. My focus is on user empathy, trying to understand and identify their context, emotions, goals and motivation. This allows me to convey a seamless narrative and clear calls to action for the projects I work on.
included.headline: UX Researcher at Microsoft WDG.

included.description: Design and development of an interactive smart office space using Amazon Alexa and Google Home to provide voice as a medium to automate tasks in conference rooms and offices. Created workflows for user interactions to help users set up meetings, reserve conference rooms, update meeting notes and post messages to conversation channels. Conducted Wizard of Oz sessions to measure the increase in productivity while using these voice-based personal assistants.
included.title: Smart Office Automation

included.description: Social Minecraft is a 4-week program focused on building social skills in children with Autism Spectrum Disorder. It is meant to facilitate social connection by bringing small groups of participants together in an educational atmosphere to play Minecraft, a game already popular among autistic children. Lessons are specifically designed to encourage conversational and cooperative play, and progress is documented and presented weekly to parents.
included.title: Social Minecraft

included.description: Worked with a group of 3 people to devise a smart gardening solution which would help users feel connected to their gardens without taking away from the actual experience. Conducted research, created designs and made a prototype for the IoT-enabled smart gardening system using sensors and data analytics to help gardeners understand exactly what their garden needs using rapid prototyping and pervasive design methods. The research consisted of photo-diary studies, qualitative 1-1 interviews, guerilla interviews, user enactments to come up with a multi-modal interface using Particle IO, Framer and Firebase.
included.title: Plants That Talk - IoT

included.description: In the summer of 2016, the Innovation Studio at School of Public Health, University of Michigan initiated a project under the supervision of Prof. Sharon Kardia and Dr. Jodyn Platt to tackle the challenge of the health disparities in population health domain. The goal of this project was to help community benefit officers make the case for investing in social determinants of health. Over the course of 10 weeks, the project team had interviewed more than 80 people from various stakeholder groups, synthesized the insights from the interviews, ideated based on our research findings, prototyped potential solutions, and iterated based on feedback received from the user testing.
included.title: Traceroot

included.description: Designed and built a smart, personified wearable device to help people cope with their socially awkward fidgeting habits by providing an alternate innocuous fidgeting tool.  Dived deep into user empathy by conducting participatory design sessions. The design promoted positive motivation and behavior change through the overall physical form, contextually engaging interactions, relaxing haptic feedback to help the users with anxiety and ADHD. Prototype was created using Arduinos and customized sensors for  tracking the fidgeting habits.
included.title: Pyramid - A smart wearable to track and improve fidgeting habits

included.description: Design and development of an interactive sound based installation with tangible interfaces using generative art and dynamic music generation. The project consisted of a 2 player tank shooting game which reacted to the user's actions and created dynamic sounds and visuals from this data. The interface switched between competitive and co-operative play by encouraging the users to create new melodies by colliding their shots with the second player. Conducted wizard of oz studies, guerilla tests and iterative prototyping to design and develop the game interaction. Custom controllers were designed to be used by the players to control the in-game units.
included.title: Tang Tanks

included.description: Helped the Ann Arbor district library with their maker spaces to introduce children to make culture by teaching them the basics of Arduino programming and creating DIY projects.
